==English==

===Etymology===
[[Cf]]. Late German ''babbeln''; D. babbelen; German ''bappeln'', ''bappern''; French ''babiller''; Italian ''babbolare''; probable origin, to keep saying ''ba'', imitative of a child learning to talk; see e.g. the building the tower of Babel.

===Noun===
#[[Idle]] talk; [[senseless]] [[prattle]]; [[gabble]]; [[twaddle]]. "This is mere moral '''babble'''." [[Milton]].
#[[Inarticulate]] [[speech]]; constant or confused [[murmur]].
#:'''Quotations'''
#:*The '''babble''' of our young children. - [[Darwin]].
#:*The '''babble''' of the stream. - [[Tennyson]].

